The England openers race off straight away, followed by the rest, and Broad raises the ball to the crowd again. A few more boos. It has been a superb performance from him. England will be delighted to keep Australia under 300, although 295 is a few more than looked likely at 132 for 6. Now it's all about the new ball again. Harris, Johnson and Siddle verses Cook, Carberry and Trott. If England get a solid base, they will be well placed for a lead.

9.45am Fifteen minutes until the action resumes. Brad Haddin approaching a second consecutive Ashes hundred at the Gabba. Australia could do with a few more of his type in the top order.

Ryan: "As an Australian, I certainly wasn't Broad's greatest fan coming into this series. However, there has been something very "Australian" (in the vein of the Rats of Tobruk and the Scrap Iron Flotilla) about his response to the media and crowd sledging since he's been here... I can't help but love his comment about singing along to the "Broad is a w****r" chant. While I won't be chearing against Australia, there'll be part of me that really doesn't mind when it's Broad taking our wickets."

9.30am How good (or bad) a total is 273 for 8 (8 for 273)? England's top order has not been prolific of late, so Ryan Harris, Mitchell Johnson and Peter Siddle could yet bring Australia back into this match. Signs of a few cracks on the pitch, too, and England likely to bat last.

Gary MacLennan: "Could we have a comment on the relative speeds of the two attacks? The English fast bowlers got down to 129 km and as far as I could see they did not pass 140km. The Aussies, by contrast, will bowl in the 136-150 range. Will that make a difference?" It's a good point, Gary. Australia's bowlers were generally quicker than England's in the previous series. Pace is one thing. But if it's off target it's no good.

Some news this morning: a man has been charged with bringing a big into the Gabba (yes, a pig...not the first time one has been brought into an Australian ground). Here's the AAP report. "Police media confirmed a man has been charged with animal cruelty. The pig, whose name is Ash, was taken to the RSPCA to be treated for dehydration."

"Some reports suggested the pig had "Broad" written on its side, in reference to English bowler Stuart Broad, who was vilified in some circles for failing to walk when he edged a ball during the last Ashes series.

Security at the ground would not confirm if this was the case."

So, that is stumps on the much-anticipated first day of this Ashes series. There is no question that this was England's day, and more specifically Stuart Broad's day - he finished with 5 for 65 and reached the 50-wicket milestone for this year. But again, the story of the day for Australia was a limp batting performance from the top six. None reached fifty, and too many fell to soft dismissals. Brad Haddin and Mitchell Johnson fought back to avoid total embarrassment, but having chosen to bat on a good pitch, the Australians should have fared much better than 8 for 273. Broad and Anderson were very good and Tremlett bowled reasonably well, but the Australian bowlers may find out tomorrow that there's not a whole lot there for them. Watch out for all the analysis from our team at the Gabba, and join us tomorrow for the second day's play.

Well, this has been a terrible start. Less than two sessions into the Ashes series and the coffee machine has broken. I've had to go get in the lift in order to drown my twitching synapses in black nirvana... Anyway, this Australia batting hasn't been too sharp, either. But they can still avoid (complete) ignominy. Had Braddin and MJ should at least get them past the 167 they made 25 years ago. Should...
